We use the central limit formulas for a random total. \[\mu_{\sum{X}} ~=~ n\cdot\mu_{X} ~=~ (97)(53.6) ~=~ 5199.2 \] \[\sigma_{\sum{X}} = \sigma_{X}\sqrt{n} = (9.03)\sqrt{97} = 88.935186\] So, we think the random total is normally distributed with a mean of 5199.2 and a standard deviation of 88.935186. \[\sum{X} \sim N(5199.2,\,88.935186) \]

Calculate a \(z\)-score for the boundary. \[z = \frac{5220-5199.2}{88.935186} = 0.2338782 \]

You can round that to \(z=0.23\) or \(z=0.24\). Any of the following probabilities will get credit. \[P(Z > 0.2338782) = 0.4075398 \] \[P(Z > 0.23) = 0.409 \] \[P(Z > 0.24) = 0.4052 \]
